**Considering Readability**

I'm currently focused on improving website readability. The existing design utilizes a very dark background (`bg-slate-950`) paired with light text colors (`text-slate-400`, `text-slate-200`, etc.). I'm exploring how to maintain the existing design, but improve it to make it more legible.


**Refining Dark Mode**

I'm now thinking about how to make the current dark mode more readable. The "easier to read" feedback is pushing me away from the low-contrast gray on black. I'm considering a "Clean Dark" or a "Clean Light" theme. I'll aim for a "Modern Clean Light/Soft Dark" approach to refine the existing dark mode, moving away from a "hacker" aesthetic and towards a more professional look, adjusting the `slate-950` background with `slate-200` and `slate-400` text.


**Prioritizing Contrast Levels**

I'm now zeroing in on boosting contrast. I'm leaning toward a high-contrast dark theme, possibly using `bg-gray-900` or `bg-neutral-900` instead of `slate-950`. I'll test `text-gray-100` for main text and `text-gray-300` for secondary, and I'll consider lighter backgrounds for cards to increase separation. I'll also try out increased leading and font weights. I'm also considering a full clean light theme, as it's generally easier to read. The goal is two columns, improved readability.


**Exploring Light Alternatives**

I'm now making substantial changes. I'm implementing a clean, minimalist light/grey theme, similar to Notion's style, moving away from the dark mode. I'm swapping the `slate-950` background to `gray-50`, and using `gray-900` and `gray-700` for headings and body text, respectively, which I believe will provide excellent readability. I'm keeping the 2-column layout and fixed sidebar. I'm also transitioning cards to white with shadows. I'm updating several files to reflect these changes.


**Adjusting Modal Contrast**

I'm now thinking specifically about how the chat modal should fit into the overall light theme. Given that light modes are better for general readability and design consistency, I'm making the modal match the light mode. I'm updating the component, ensuring it is a consistent element and improves the user experience.


**Defining Final Styling**

I'm now determining the final styles for the application. I'm focusing on the light theme's UI elements, specifically the chat modal, cards, and buttons. I'm finalizing Tailwind classes, such as the white background, subtle borders, and shadows for the cards. I'm updating specific files with these classes and styling, ensuring consistency.


**Refining Visual Consistency**

I'm now implementing the theme updates to several components, focusing on visual consistency. I've updated `Sidebar.tsx`, replacing white text with gray-900 and slate-400 with gray-600. I removed `prose-invert` for a consistent dark-on-light look. The Portfolio component has a sticky header and tabs with specific styling. Additionally, I've styled the `ProjectCard.tsx` and `ChatModal.tsx` components. I will also be updating `App.tsx`'s background image for subtle light mode compatibility.


**Defining Light Mode Baseline**

I'm now generating XML to define the updates needed for a light mode-based application theme. I've focused on `index.html`, specifying the switch to global light mode styles to improve overall readability.


**Adjusting Component Styles**

I'm presently refactoring components to adopt the light theme's design. The button styling is a top priority, and I'm updating its variants to align with the high-contrast light scheme. I'm focusing on the visual consistency throughout the UI.


**Refining Button Styles**

I'm now revising the button component, considering primary, secondary, outline, and AI variants. I'm focusing on Tailwind classes for backgrounds, text, and hover states, and ensuring visual consistency with light mode's high-contrast scheme, and adapting `ProjectCard.tsx`'s card styling and soft shadow implementation.

```text
import React from 'react';
interface ButtonProps extends React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'outline' | 'ai';
  fullWidth?: boolean;
  icon?: React.ReactNode;
  className?: string;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ variant = 'primary', fullWidth = false, icon, className, children, ...props }) => {
  const baseStyles = "inline-flex items-center px-4 py-2 border rounded-md text-sm font-medium focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-offset-2 disabled:opacity-50 disabled:cursor-not-allowed shadow-sm";

  const variants = {
    primary: "bg-indigo-600 hover:bg-indigo-700 text-white focus:ring-indigo-500 shadow-indigo-200",
    secondary: "bg-white hover:bg-gray-50 text-gray-700 focus:ring-gray-200 border border-gray-200 hover:border-gray-300",
    outline: "bg-transparent border border-gray-300 hover:border-gray-400 text-gray-600 hover:text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50",
    ai: "bg-gradient-to-r from-indigo-600 to-violet-600 hover:from-indigo-700 hover:to-violet-700 text-white shadow-indigo-200 border border-transparent"
  };

  const widthClass = fullWidth ? "w-full" : "";

  return (
    <button 
      className={`${baseStyles} ${variants[variant]} ${widthClass} ${className}`}
      {...props}
    >
      {icon && <span className="mr-2">{icon}</span>}
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};

export default Button;
```


**Optimizing Visual Feedback**

I'm now iterating on the visual response of the buttons. I've integrated subtle shadow effects to enhance the visual distinction. Also, I'm improving the hover and focus states for better user feedback and accessibility. I'm focusing on ensuring these styles remain consistent across different button variants.

